The federal government will engage more private developers to deliver more houses under the Federal Integrated Staff Housing (FISH) programme, the Head of Service of the Federation, Mrs. Winifred Oyo-Ita has said. Speaking yesterday at the Opening of the Abuja International Housing Show, 2019 in Abuja, Oyo-Ita who was represented by the Permanent Secretary, HOS, Mrs Didi Wilson-Jack said under the FISH programme, the federal government has engaged 34 real estate developers to build quality and affordable houses for civil servant in the country. She said currently, there are about 1,300 housing units at various stage of development and about 500 of them were allocated to the uptakers. She said the FISH was conceptualised in 2013 to improve the provision of housing to civil servants in the country. She assured that the government will engage more private sector under the project. Oyo-Ita said the FISH has over 55, 000 off takers. “Some public servants have already taken possession of their houses.  Some of the houses they have taken possession are in Kuje and Karu of the FCT,” she said. She said the program operates in a flexible financing model which allows for payment of houses either from the Federal Government staff Housing Scheme or finance from the Federal Mortgage Bank of Nigeria (FMBN).  Federal workers to get 1000 houses in 6 months FG commissions 151 'FISH' houses in Kuje Housing scheme will cover all federal workers  – Oyo-Ita Dear Esteemed reader, As part of our drive to keep improving the content of our newspaper, we are conducting a readership survey to enable us serve you better. Kindly take two minutes of your time to fill in this questionnaire. Thank you for your time. Click here to begin